        "content": "<p>In category theory, we have this perspective that we should focus attention on maps, on the relationships between objects, rather than on the objects themselves. What's your favorite examples of people giving a schpiel about this? Blog posts, snippets from books or papers, MO/SE answers, or even just giving your own take right now, are all welcome.</p>",
        "id": 247582684,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1627565212
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Verbs over nouns.</p>",
        "id": 247582916,
        "sender_full_name": "Simon Burton",
        "timestamp": 1627565316
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't have a favorite one, but the <a href=\"https://www.math3ma.com/blog/the-yoneda-perspective\">The Yoneda Perspective</a> is very well written.</p>",
        "id": 247583003,
        "sender_full_name": "Henry Story",
        "timestamp": 1627565364
